{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 02:54:11.447298", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report\\n\\nScope and approach\\n- Verified L3 reachability across the OSPF-based enterprise fabric.\\n- Validated service access paths: DNS, the Nginx load balancer (web99.local), public web servers (web0.local–web3.local), and backend isolation.\\n- Inspected key device configs/paths (server_access_router FRR, load_balancer IP/DNS config and Nginx upstreams).\\n- Used: reachability/ICMP tests, curl timing tests, host DNS configuration checks, and FRR route/OSPF inspection.\\n\\nSummary of current health\\n- Core routing/OSPF: Healthy. Server and access networks are advertised and reachable end-to-end. Server-access router shows stable OSPF adjacency and summary routes for all host subnets.\\n- DNS path for clients: Healthy. Hosts use 10.200.0.2 (dns_server). Latency to DNS is ~2–3 ms; name lookup times during HTTP tests are a few milliseconds.\\n- Load balancer service (web99.local): Healthy from clients. TTFB around 0.21–0.38 s, total ~1.0–1.2 s. No reachability issues observed.\\n- Policy segmentation: As designed, clients cannot reach backend servers on 20.200.0.0/24 (HTTP returns 000, pings do not complete). The 20.200.0.0/24 network is not advertised into OSPF (confirmed), so backends are not directly accessible from host subnets.\\n- Public web servers (web0.local–web3.local): Reachable but responses are slow (see anomalies).\\n\\nDetailed findings and evidence\\n\\n1) End-to-end reachability across OSPF\\n- Bulk ICMP tests from many clients across areas to other hosts show 0% packet loss and sub-5 ms RTTs, indicating the routed fabric is operating normally without loss or excessive latency.\\n- server_access_router routes:\\n  - 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected and present.\\n  - All 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 host subnets learned via OSPF are present with stable timers.\\n  - OSPF on server_access_router has 1 neighbor on eth7 (to core), backbone area only, and a healthy LSA set; SPF times are short.\\n\\n2) DNS service for clients\\n- Hosts’ resolv.conf points to nameserver 10.200.0.2.\\n- Pings to 10.200.0.2: 0% loss, ~2–3 ms.\\n- curl name lookup time for web*.local is consistently small (typically <10 ms), showing DNS resolution is responsive and not a contributor to slow page loads.\\n\\n3) Load balancer (web99.local) path and backends\\n- Nginx upstream on load_balancer points to:\\n  - 20.200.0.2:80\\n  - 20.200.0.3:80\\n  - 20.200.0.4:80\\n- load_balancer interfaces and routes:\\n  - eth0: 10.200.0.7/24, default via 10.200.0.1\\n  - eth1: 20.200.0.1/24 (directly connected to backends)\\n- From load_balancer to backends:\\n  - ICMP to 20.200.0.{2,3,4} succeeds with ~0.6–1.5 ms typical RTTs.\\n  - HTTP to backends returns 200 with TTFB 0.25–0.44 s and total ~1.05–1.25 s, indicating healthy backend responsiveness from the LB.\\n- From hosts to web99.local:\\n  - Successful with TTFB ~0.21–0.38 s and total ~1.0–1.2 s.\\n- From hosts to 20.200.0.{2,3,4}:\\n  - HTTP code 000, no route/access, matching the segmentation requirement that backends are not directly accessible.\\n\\n4) Public-facing Apache web servers (web0.local–web3.local)\\n- From multiple clients:\\n  - web0.local: starttransfer ~2.2–3.7 s; total ~3.0–4.5 s.\\n  - web1.local: starttransfer ~0.47–1.43 s; total ~1.2–2.3 s.\\n  - web2.local: starttransfer ~1.24–1.51 s; total ~2.0–2.3 s.\\n  - web3.local: starttransfer ~0.19–1.30 s; total ~1.0–2.1 s.\\n- Name lookup and connect times are small (few ms), and network RTTs are single-digit milliseconds, indicating that the multi-second delays are not due to routing or link latency.\\n\\nAnomalies detected\\n\\nA) Load balancer local DNS configuration is missing\\n- On load_balancer, /etc/resolv.conf is empty; attempting curl http://web99.local from the LB itself yields http_code:000 (no resolution).\\n- Impact: Only affects on-box name resolution (monitoring/health checks or any name-based operations executed on the LB host). Client traffic is unaffected because:\\n  - Nginx upstreams are configured with IP addresses.\\n  - Client DNS resolution is performed by DNS server 10.200.0.2, which is healthy.\\n\\nLocalization and root cause:\\n- Faulty device: load_balancer.\\n- Root cause: Missing DNS resolver configuration on the LB host.\\n\\nB) Slow TTFB to public web servers (web0.local–web3.local)\\n- Consistent multi-second TTFB observed from hosts to webX.local despite low network latency and fast DNS resolution.\\n- web99.local (LB) shows much better TTFB, and LB-to-backend HTTP checks are healthy, isolating the slowness to the public Apache web servers themselves rather than the network.\\n- This suggests an application-side performance issue on web_server_0..3 rather than a network fault.\\n\\nLocalization and root cause:\\n- Faulty devices: web_server_0..3 (application layer).\\n- Root cause: Application/webserver processing delays (not attributable to DNS or network transport based on timing breakdown).\\n\\nItems explicitly verified as normal/expected\\n\\n- OSPF routing stability and advertisement of 10.200.0.0/24 into the fabric.\\n- Inter-area host connectivity (no loss, low RTTs).\\n- DNS service 10.200.0.2 responsiveness from clients.\\n- Backend network (20.200.0.0/24) isolation from clients by lack of routing — matches design intent.\\n- Load balancer path to backends over eth1 is reachable and fast; client access to web99.local over eth0 is responsive.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- Fabric and routing are healthy; no evidence of network-level packet loss, misrouting, or OSPF instability.\\n- Two anomalies identified:\\n  1) load_balancer host lacks a DNS resolver (on-box only).\\n  2) Public Apache web servers (web0.local–web3.local) exhibit elevated server-side TTFB; network and DNS are not the cause.\\n- Backend isolation is enforced correctly and not an anomaly., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='bd3f01da-b9b2-4470-9f76-973e2fde98fd'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
